bug.short_desc: Mailbox deletion is not recursive / bails out

long_desc.thetext:
Upon creation of a set of mailboxes like so:
> user/john.doe@example.org > user/john.doe/Archive@example.org > user/john.doe/Drafts@example.org > user/john.doe/Sent@example.org > user/john.doe/Spam@example.org > user/john.doe/Trash@example.org
Deleting mailbox user/john.doe@example.org results in a segfault:
> Feb 26 19:11:23 kolab imaps[10826]: Rename: example.org!user.john^doe -> example.org!DELETED.user.john^doe.512CFACB > Feb 26 19:11:23 kolab notifyd[10723]: EVENT, , , , "{"event":"QuotaWithin","timestamp":"2013-02-26T19:11:23.253+01:00","service":"imaps","uri":"imap://john^doe@example.org@kolab.example.org/INBOX","maxMessages":0,"messages":0}" > Feb 26 19:11:23 kolab imaps[10826]: Deleted mailbox example.org!user.john^doe > Feb 26 19:11:23 kolab master[10712]: process type:SERVICE name:imaps path:/usr/lib/cyrus-imapd/imapd age:1.365s pid:10826 signaled to death by signal 11 (Segmentation fault, core dumped)
I'll look at this.
Jeroen, I'm have some difficulty reproducing this from the information provided. Can you send the imapd.conf, the config.status, and a backtrace from the core?

Thanks, I'll give it a go when I have a chance, and maybe this is resolved or get back with some proper backtrace.

I still haven't been able to generate a crash or any Valgrind error that might lead to a crash. I really will need some kind of backtrace (or core file and matching imapd binary, I should be able to work it out from there even without debuginfo)
Anyway experiment shows that this:
> Feb 26 19:11:23 kolab notifyd[10723]: EVENT, , , , "{"event":"QuotaWithin","timestamp":"2013-02-26T19:11:23.253+01:00","service":"imaps","uri":"imap://john^doe@example.org@kolab.example.org/INBOX","maxMessages":0,"messages":0}"
is completely bogus. An event is being generated for a quota resource which has no limit set. Also, only one event is ever generated even though in theory multiple resources can fall below quota at the same time. Plus there's a memory leak when events are generated on folders which have a specialuse set.
Sebastian or I have fixed these problems. Can you please re-test with all of the following commits applied?
6104b5c mboxevent: fix memleak in _enabled_for_mailbox 9877599 mboxevent: maybe generate multiple QuotaWithin b22868b mboxevent: cleaner QuotaWithin check d9d97f4 mboxevent: don't send QuotaWithin notification on negative quota ed6233a mboxevent: link next event to previous one when freeing fa0558d mboxevent: translate internal user name to external

Yes it is an oversight. RFC 5423 provides no recommendation regarding this case. It should be possible to send a single notification: diskUsed/diskQuota and messages/maxMessages seem to coexist in a QuotaWithin notification.
> b22868b mboxevent: cleaner QuotaWithin check Thanks, very nice.

(In reply to comment #12) > > 9877599 mboxevent: maybe generate multiple QuotaWithin > > Yes it is an oversight. RFC 5423 provides no recommendation regarding this > case. > It should be possible to send a single notification: diskUsed/diskQuota and > messages/maxMessages seem to coexist in a QuotaWithin notification.
I think two events is probably better. It's just as easy for us to generate, and it won't behave differently later if the times at which the two resources are decremented is later changed. Also, event listeners are probably more likely to just expect the simple case.
But I'm not fussy about it.
While we're on that topic, it seems like we haven't got any way to report going below quota on the two Cyrus-specific quota resources. We just generate a QuotaWithin event with no useful fields in it. We should either add vendor-specific fields (e.g. vnd.cmu.folders and vnd.cmu.maxFolders) or not generate events.

Guys,
can we move the spurious event notifications to a different ticket? For this ticket, I'm not so much concerned with additional notifications, nor whether they are useful or not.
The original problem persists in today's git origin/master HEAD (at 771b52).
Once I've figured out (again) how to get a backtrace in gdb, I'll report back ;-)

Looking at the code, it looks like any filename in the proc directory starting with a non-numeric character will cause proc_foreach_helper() to attempt to parse the proc directory itself as a proc file. A litle bit more error checking would come in handy.

I'm temporarily unable to build or test, but this should fix it:
The following changes since commit 6104b5c17c5eed53ed0a3ce3415fd46216771b52: Greg Banks (1): mboxevent: fix memleak in _enabled_for_mailbox
are available in the git repository at:
ssh://git@github.com/gnb/cyrus-imapd.git bz3781
Greg Banks (2): proc: whitespace fixes proc: better error check in proc_foreach
imap/proc.c | 20 +++++++++++++------- 1 files changed, 13 insertions(+), 7 deletions(-)

Ooh, it gets better: proc_register() creates the proc files in a non-atomic fashion, so that there are racy states when the proc files are empty or contain a mixture of valid and invalid information. And empty files cause a crash in proc_foreach_helper. Try these commits:
